Signal Archive Account Page Refactor Spec
Tier-Aware Layout + Cost Discipline
Objective
Refactor the /account/[id] page to support tier-aware tracking modes while preserving the existing backend and ingestion architecture.
This refactor must:
Preserve current backend data structures where possible
Avoid introducing new ingestion costs
Minimize API, database, compute, and third-party usage
Maintain current visual credibility and minimal design language
This is a UI refactor with efficiency constraints, not a backend expansion.
Critical Cost Constraint
Until our custom ingestion “lifehack” is completed and operational:
Do NOT add any new third-party X/Twitter ingestion calls.
Do NOT introduce automatic backfills.
Do NOT increase SocialData.tools or similar paid API usage.
Do NOT expand tracking scope for identity-only accounts.
Do NOT trigger expensive historical fetches automatically.
All new UI behavior must operate strictly on:
Already captured data
Already stored metadata
Already attested events
Progressive disclosure only. Nothing expensive by default.
Tracking Modes
Some accounts operate in different tracking modes:
FULL_ARCHIVE
Statements (tweets) captured
Deletions detected
Identity continuity tracked
Attestations recorded
IDENTITY_ONLY
Handle continuity tracked
Limited metadata tracked (e.g., created region, created date if available)
Attestations recorded
No statement capture
No deletion tracking
The UI must reflect these modes without looking broken or incomplete.
Page Structure
Route
/account/:stableUserId
Layout Overview (Hybrid A + Receipt Card)
1. Receipt Card (Top Block)
Screenshotable citation block including:
Current handle
Stable User ID (copyable)
Tracking Mode chip
Observed since
Coverage summary (auto-generated based on mode)
“View latest proof” button
This establishes credibility immediately.
2. Account Header Section
Includes:
@handle (large)
Optional display name
Optional category
Optional metadata fields (if present)
Stats row (mode-aware)
Stats logic:
FULL_ARCHIVE:
Statements count
Deletions count
Handle changes count
IDENTITY_ONLY:
Handle changes count
Metadata changes count (if tracked)
Do not render irrelevant zeroed metrics.
3. Segmented Control (Always Render Same Structure)
Always render in this order:
Activity | Statements | Deletions | Identity | Attestations
Behavior rules:
FULL_ARCHIVE → all enabled
IDENTITY_ONLY → Statements + Deletions disabled
Disabled state:
Muted styling
Not clickable
Tooltip: “Not tracked for this account’s mode.”
Do not remove disabled tabs from DOM.
Tab Behavior
Activity (Default Tab)
Unified chronological event feed.
Possible event types:
STATEMENT_CAPTURED (FULL_ARCHIVE only)
STATEMENT_DELETED (FULL_ARCHIVE only)
HANDLE_CHANGED
METADATA_CHANGED (if applicable)
ATTESTED
Identity-only accounts still show:
HANDLE_CHANGED
ATTESTED
Activity must always function.
Statements (FULL_ARCHIVE only)
Reuse existing tweet list UI.
Requirements:
Paginated or infinite scroll
Thin payload (summary only)
Full proof available via existing proof page
Must not load entire history by default.
Deletions (FULL_ARCHIVE only)
Reuse existing deletions list UI.
Requirements:
Paginated
Efficient queries
No heavy joins
Proof links preserved
Identity
Always enabled.
Shows:
Handle history timeline
First observed handle
Current handle
Change timestamps
Metadata changes (if tracked)
Must load lazily if history is large.
Attestations
Always enabled.
Shows:
Hash
Event type
HCS topic ID
Transaction ID
Timestamp
External proof link
Must not re-fetch heavy verification data unnecessarily.
Efficiency Requirements
These are mandatory:
Do not fetch all data on initial page load.
Load only what the default tab requires.
Use thin payloads for list views.
Paginate all large collections.
Avoid per-request aggregate recomputation.
Use existing stored counters when available.
Identity-only accounts must never trigger statement/deletion queries.
Any new fetch must include a code comment explaining cost impact.
Prefer cached or statically revalidated data when safe.
Avoid additional HCS writes triggered by UI behavior.
